Yeah, I've tried it with a real input as well, which works in the normal TF model, and also TF Lite. But I got the same error with the real input in the converted ONNX model, and if not exactly the same, it was still about an axis dimension mismatch.

It'll be difficult for me to share a sample image, as the input image goes through a lot of pre-processing before going into the model with appropriate input dimensions. Also, as it's a multi-input model, there are different inputs like the anchors and meta data along with the image.

What if instead of passing zero arrays, you randomly populate the inputs with garbage values?

Is there a way you can share inputs as serialized numpy arrays (after pre-processing and all that needs to get done before passing it onto the graph) ?

Garbage data isn't really too different from np.zeros() for this exercise, it is hard to really prove that the garbage data had detections/regions of interest like a "real" image. 

I expect to see the same error even for a "valid" input with 0 detections (something cryptic about an operator failing a runtime check and one of the dims being 0). We had the exact same scenario a while back with a Mask RCNN model exported from PyTorch that was basically failing a node for inputs that had 0 detections. Unfortunately, ORT can't do too much about these node execution failures if it violates the ONNX spec (like in this case, we are concatenating inputs in which the non-concat axes' dim values differed - this is a direct violation of the ONNX spec for the Concat operator). It is upto the model to handle such cases more gracefully and exit the graph prior to such nodes. When we bought this up to the Torch exporter group at that time, they had acknowledged this and said they will account for this in future.

This is the reason why we strongly feel that we require a "real" image producing (at-least one) detection to even investigate (even then, the issue could still be one of conversion/export but atleast it is more concrete to go on than garbage data/np.zeros()).

issue.title: Loosen validation checks in Concat to unblock execution of model in #8020

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: 

If the Loop operator has an iteration count of zero, the pedantic way to deal with it would be to execute the subgraph and obtain the output shapes of the scan outputs and pre-pend their shapes with 0. This preserves the "right" shape information for downstream operators to work with these empty outputs from Loop. In our implementation of Loop, we avoid executing the subgraph (as an optimization to save execution cycles - since the scan outputs of Loop with an iteration count of 0 are going to be empty anyway). We do the best we can with respect to the shape(s) of these empty scan outputs. We use the ONNX shape inference information to compose the shape(s) of these scan outputs. If we encounter symbolic dimensions, we use '0' instead (trying to compose a shape that has the same rank as the ONNX shape inferred shape atleast). In case, no rank information is available, we log a warning and just use a shape of {0} for these scan outputs. The "lossy" nature of this shape composition process means downstream node checks need to be less pedantic in their shape validations as well. This change loosens one such pedantic check in `Concat`.

In the OP's model in #8020, multiple Loops feed into a Concat, and in some cases, atleast one Loop feeding into the Concat has an iteration count of zero and the runtime check in Concat fails when trying to concatenate inputs like this (simplified for illustration only): [2, y1, y2, y3] and [0, 0, 0, 0] on axis = 0. The check complains that the axes not being concatenated on are not the equal. We make this check less restrictive. 

This PR may seem a bit hacky but this is quite an uncommon graph structure and there is nothing to lose by making a check less restrictive in one operator to unblock model execution.

The corner case handling in `GatherND` is needed for this model as well. With these changes, the model runs fine on CPU and CUDA.

**Motivation and Context**
Resolve https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/8020
